Mixed-species flocking is a common phenomenon in birds in tropical and temperate habitats worldwide, and has been the subject of much research (

; 

; Kotagama and 

; 

). Mixed flocks are thought to provide their participants with benefits arising from increased foraging efficiency and decreased predation risk (

). However, despite an extensive literature spanning close to a century and a half (

), several aspects of the dynamics of mixed-species flocking still remain poorly explored and unclear.

By comparing observed participation in mixed-species flocks with expected participation based purely on the overall abundances of participant species, we characterize species as participating more than expected, as expected, or less than expected in mixed flocks. This approach takes into account the availability of species to join flocks, and is among the first attempts to do so in characterizing species participation (

). 

also use abundance data to characterize flocking propensity. However, their approach measures the probability of a species being “left behind” by a moving flock, rather than comparing expected participation (based on abundance) with empirically observed participation. We also explore how the degree of participation by different species is related to aspects of the ecology of species, specifically with factors such as body mass, diet and foraging method.

We expected that flocking species would be predominantly insectivorous, because unlike localized resources such as nectar and fruit that might advertise themselves, arthropods are likely to be more scattered and cryptic. This property of the resource might require insectivores to keep company with other species to learn foraging locations or benefit from facilitatory behaviours of other species (e.g. 

; 

). We also expected that the “core” of a flock (composed of species that participate regularly in flocks) would be composed of species that were predominantly insectivorous, compared with attendant species, which might include arthropods in their diet in addition to other resources, and therefore might join flocks only temporarily to satisfy their dietary insect requirements. We finally hypothesized that the core of a flock would be made up of species that exchanged complementary benefits arising from specialized feeding behaviours. This might reduce interspecific competition arising from similar ecologies and also result in facilitatory foraging benefits. We therefore predicted that the core of a flock should be heterogeneous with respect to the representation of foraging methods adopted by different species (especially when compared with attendant species).

Fieldwork was carried out in the Namdapha National Park (27 ◦ 23 ′ 30 ′′ to
27 ◦ 39 ′ 40 ′′ N
and 96 ◦ 15 ′ 2 ′′ to
96 ◦ 58 ′ 33 ′′ E
) in Changlang district , eastern Arunachal Pradesh , India , from early
December 2007
to mid-March 2008. Namdapha is situated in the Eastern Himalaya , a global Biodiversity Hotspot , and an Important Bird Area with about 500 bird species (
). Annual rainfall varies from 1500 to 3500 mm , most of which falls during the southwest monsoon months of April to October (
). Sampling was conducted in the Hornbill and Musathi areas in the buffer zone of the national park, at altitudes ranging from
500 to 650 m above sea level
. The habitat in this area is composed of dipterocarp-dominated lowland tropical evergreen forest (
)
.

Mixed-species flocks were defined as a group of two or more species moving in the same direction (

). Data on mixed-species flocks were recorded on the established line transects (during sampling for bird abundances), and also opportunistically along pre-existing trails from 13.00 to 15.30 hr. We avoided sampling during the early morning (when flocks would be forming), and the late evening (when they would be disbanding), to minimize any biases in the results that might arise from time of day. For mixed flocks encountered on transects, species composition of the flock was recorded, and for each species cluster in the flock, cluster size, detection bearing and detection distance were noted. These data were also used in species abundance estimation. During opportunistic sampling of mixed flocks, species composition alone was recorded. We considered flocks recorded on the same transect but on different sampling occasions independent of each other (

) because individuals join and leave flocks over very short time frames, and are “potentially interactive from minute to minute” (

).

In estimating the detection function and detection probability of bird species, we sought to take into account differences in detectability across species. We divided species into three “detection classes” based on their median detection distances, each class containing an equal number of species. This approach assumes intra-class homogeneity in species detection functions and models multi-species data more parsimoniously by exploiting species’ similarity in detectability (

). The detection function for each of these three classes was estimated separately using the program DISTANCE (version 5.0, 

), and these detection functions were used along with the species-specific encounter rates to estimate the cluster abundance of each species.

a. 
Core species
. Species for which the observed number of occurrences in mixed-species flocks exceeded the upper 95% confidence limit of their occurrences expected by abundance alone. Our definition of core species is qualitatively similar to previous definitions (

; 

), which are also based on the degree of species participation.

b. Regular attendants . Species for which the observed number of flock occurrences fell within the 95% confidence intervals of the distribution of their expected occurrences. Although attendant species are usually defined functionally as species that are not “nuclear” (i.e. not involved in initiating or maintaining mixed-species flocks; e.g.
), we apply this term here to describe species that do not form the “core” of a flock.
also used degree of participation to define “attendant species” and to further classify attendants into usual, regular and accidental attendants.

Species were classified as insectivores, omnivores, nectarivores, frugivores, granivores or carnivores based on the degree of predominance of a particular food component in their diet as given in secondary sources (

; 

; 

; 

). Insectivorous species were classified as foliage gleaners, bark gleaners, hoverers or salliers based on the predominant foraging method of each species as reported in secondary sources (

; 

; 

) and from observations made during the study. The definitions of gleaning, hovering and sallying are based on descriptions in 

. Gleaners are species that forage mainly by picking stationary prey items off a substrate such as foliage or tree bark; hence foliage gleaners and bark gleaners. Hoverers are species that forage predominantly by picking stationary prey items from a substrate while in flight. Salliers are species that forage mainly by pursuing flying prey and capturing these when in flight (described as “hawking” by 

). Body mass data were obtained from 

. In most cases, body mass was provided as a range from minimum to maximum, and we used the mid-point of this range in our analysis. Data on foraging heights were obtained during line-transect sampling. For each individual bird detected on a transect walk, the stratum in which the bird was detected (understorey, midstorey or canopy) was recorded.

